FT  19 MAY 93 / International Company News: Telecom NZ suffers downturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HEAVY restructuring costs have led to a sharp fall in profits at Telecom
Corporation of New Zealand.
The company, controlled by Bell Atlantic and Ameritech, has announced a
profit of NZDollars 108m (USDollars 58.6m) for the financial year to March
31, in line with analysts' predictions, after absorbing a restructuring
charge of NZDollars 350m after tax. The restructuring includes laying off
5,500 staff by 1995.
Mr Peter Shirtcliffe, the chairman, said earnings excluding abnormal
restructuring costs would have been NZDollars 458m, compared with NZDollars
444m in 1991-92.
The chairman said the company was expecting another pleasing year, and
intended continuing to increase its dividends to shareholders. The company
increased its final dividend by one cent to 8.5 cents a share.
