<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / International Company News: US energy group sues bid rival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PARKER &amp; Parsley, the US energy group which last week agreed to pay Dollars
448m for Prudential Securities' troubled energy investment partnerships, is
suing Louis Dreyfus Natural Gas, a rival US energy company which has
submitted a higher bid for the partnerships, for attempting to interfere in
the transaction.
Graham Royalty, a firm which was a general partner in the loss-making
partnerships along with Prudential, is also named as a defendant in the
lawsuit filed in Texas.
Parker claims that Dreyfus 'maliciously interfered' with the merger
agreement between Parker and Prudential and that Graham Royalty breached the
merger agreement and committed conspiracy and fraud by negotiating with
Dreyfus.
The lawsuit follows a series of confusing events. On Monday Prudential
agreed to sell its partnerships to Parker for Dollars 448m but a few days
later, under pressure from investors in the partnerships, it was forced to
reveal that a counter-offer worth Dollars 510m had already been made by
Dreyfus.
At the time, Prudential said that it did not accept the higher offer because
there was not enough information in the bid for it to be evaluated properly.
Prudential has since said it will consider the bid once Dreyfus has provided
a full financing commitment for its offer, which Dreyfus said it will
provide in the next week.
The affair is being watched closely by investors in the Prudential energy
partnerships. After the partnerships racked up big losses in the late 1980s
because of a slump in the domestic energy and property businesses, the
investors sued Prudential for misleading them over the risks involved in
buying into the partnerships.
</TEXT>
