<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Inquiry into carrier contract bids: Audit probe to decide
how VSEL undercut Swan Hunter by Pounds 50m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE, IVOR OWEN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN IMMEDIATE inquiry is to be launched by the National Audit Office into the
bidding war for a helicopter carrier order that left Swan Hunter, the
struggling shipbuilder, facing closure.
The NAO, the government's spending watchdog, decided on the move yesterday
after a meeting between Sir John Bourn, comptroller and auditor general, and
Sir Nicholas Bonsor, chairman of the Commons defence select committee.
It hopes to report back to parliament before MPs rise for the summer recess
in July or August.
The inquiry will have to decide, among other things, how the victorious
consortium of Cumbria-based VSEL and the Kvaerner Govan merchant shipyard in
Glasgow was able to undercut Swan by as much as Pounds 50m on an order
believed to be worth about Pounds 170m. Swan Hunter is the last working
shipbuilder in north-east England.
The NAO said yesterday that it aimed to check whether bid procedures were
carried out fairly. The circumstances surrounding the order were the 'kind
of thing' it might have looked into even without Sir Nicholas's approach.
Sir Nicholas said it was 'a matter of concern' that Swan was at risk. 'It is
very worrying. Certain allegations have been made about the way the contract
was tendered.'
The move came as Mr Nick Brown, Labour MP for Newcastle East and frontbench
spokesman, claimed additions to the original specifications ordered by the
Ministry of Defence had forced Swan to add Pounds 30m to its original
tender. This led to a final price of about Pounds 200m.
He said Swan had been unable to absorb the cost of the additional work. VSEL
had done so through the 'enormous profits' made on the 'cost-plus' Trident
submarine contract. He wanted the inquiry to reach a conclusion about the
level of subsidy in the VSEL bid.
'The plain truth is that those in the Ministry of Defence and higher up in
the government never had any intention of allowing Swan Hunter to win the
contract.'
Mr Tony Newton, leader of the Commons, said Mr Brown had not served any good
purpose by suggesting that there had been 'some kind of conspiracy'.
In a separate move, Price Waterhouse - the receiver appointed to Swan's UK
companies last week - confirmed it had reached an agreement with the MoD.
This would permit it to meet this month's wage payment to Swan's 1,750
manual workforce, due this Friday. Under the agreement, work on three Type
23 frigates would continue until at least May 28.
News of the inquiry triggered a mixed response. Mr Stephen Byers, the Labour
MP in whose Wallsend constituency Swan is headquartered, complained it would
not 'save a single job on Tyneside'. Mr David Clark, shadow defence
secretary, said the scope of the inquiry should be expanded.
</TEXT>
