<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Row over Steinkuhler grows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL, JUDY DEMPSEY and DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, BERLIN, FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMAN politicians and rank-and-file trade union members last night called
for the resignation of Mr Franz Steinkuhler, leader of the IG Metall
engineering workers' union, from board memberships for alleged
insider-dealing in shares in a Daimler-Benz holding company.
The affair also brought new pressure for an urgent law to ban insider
trading on the German stock exchanges.
Mr Steinkuhler, the leading trade union member on Daimler's supervisory
board, has denied the insider dealing charge but admitted buying almost DM1m
(Pounds 400,000) worth of shares in the holding company, MAH. The shares
increased in value by almost 20 per cent after a Daimler board decision to
exchange them for full company shares.
Mr Otto Lambsdorff, leader of the Free Democratic party in the ruling
coalition in Bonn, said Mr Steinkuhler should resign all his supervisory
board positions - in Volkswagen, Thyssen and Daimler-Benz - if there was any
confirmation that he had abused his position.
Mr Heiner Geissler, a deputy leader of the Christian Democrat group in
parliament, and seven works councils at the Mercedes-Benz plant in
Stuttgart, the automobile subsidiary of Daimler, said he should resign.
A senior union official in east Germany, where IG Metall members are on
strike, was clearly shocked by the allegations.
There was also some sympathy, however, for Mr Steinkuhler, who has won a
reputation as a tough and successful negotiator in more than six years as
leader of the country's largest trade union.
The pressure for legislation to outlaw insider trading, promised by the
German government for the end of the year, was stepped up in Frankfurt
yesterday.
A thoroughly modern union man, Page 2 Editorial Comment, Page 25
