FT  19 MAY 93 / Observer: Paying up
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Among the deft bits of prudent accounting which helped the Institute of
Chartered Accountants in England and Wales to get out of the red in 1992,
one item stands out. The institute's Pounds 38,000 surplus is more than
accounted for by a doubling, to Pounds 109,000, in income from 'maintenance
of professional and ethical standards' - in other words, a substantial
increase in the number and level of fines against misbehaving members.
