<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Male summer absenteeism strikes the nation today, oddly coinciding with the
first one-day Cricket International between England and Australia (BBC1,
10.40am). This Morning (ITV, 10.35am) tries hard to beat off the cricket
competition by offering something utterly new - Loyd Grossman on a
gastronomic journey through France. The BBC still performs a public service.
One of its more valuable offerings is Open Space (BBC2, 7.40pm), where
members of the public use its facilities to make programmes. Tonight's is by
Jill Wright, director of the National Library Campaign, fighting the decline
in library funding. Eat Your Greens (Channel 4, 8.30pm) is a small-screen
pleasure. An instructive food programme; beautifully filmed and edited; and
presented by a very unsnobby cook, Sophie Grigson. But the joy of the day
for London commuters like myself will be watching the first of a new series
of Inside Story (BBC1, 9.30pm). It promises to go behind the scenes of
British Rail and explain why things go so wrong. Bad Company (BBC2, 9pm)
concludes the dramatisation of the Carl Bridgewater murder.
