<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Business and the Environment: Green maze guide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The environmental industry is hardly short of directories. But the recently
published Entec Directory of Environmental Technology* is one of the more
ambitious, and if comprehensiveness is the criterion, one of the most
successful.
Its foreword, by Nigel Bell of Imperial College, London, repeats the common
refrain that 'environmental issues present not only unparalleled challenges
but also unique opportunities'. Those unsubstantiated remarks are too
casually made in the environmental industry, given the importance of the
question. However, the attraction of the directory is not the text but its
extensive charts.
Its 1,000 pages in English, French, German and Spanish list 20,000 companies
in Europe supplying environmental technology. The first 800 are devoted to
classification: water, air, solid waste, hazardous waste, waste planning and
management, noise and vibration, energy, and 'environmental organisations
and consultancies'.
Each section is then subdivided again - for example, water is sliced into 14
mini-sections on water treatment, water pollution, sewerage and so on. The
companies which participate in those areas are then marked down one side of
a grid, while 30 products, such as fluoridation and desalination, are marked
along the top.
This categorisation - almost 1,000 groupings - is both a strength and a
weakness. It is enormously detailed, but if you are not sure which
sub-section you should be looking for, you may find it less helpful.
Provided readers are using it to help them locate technology suppliers, they
should be satisfied, but it is less useful in getting an overview of what
companies do, or of their size. The last 200 pages, though, contain an
excellent index of all companies' names and telephone numbers.
*The Entec Directory of Environmental Technology. Pounds 125, 1024pp,
Earthscan Publications, 120 Pentonville Road London N1 9JN.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
