<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Bank says government inflation target achievable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of England is reasonably confident that the government will be able
to hold underlying inflation below its 4 per cent target ceiling over the
next year and a half.
Contrary to some reports at the weekend the Bank's second quarterly
inflation report, published yesterday, suggested that the outlook for
underlying inflation to the end of year, as measured by the retail prices
index excluding mortgage interest payments, 'is no worse, and probably
slightly better' than indicated three months ago.
Changes since the last inflation report 'have lowered slightly both the
expected inflation rate and the probability of breaching the 4 per cent
limit during the course of this year,' the Bank says. 'The probability of
breaching the target next year may be a little greater than previously
envisaged, but the Bank's central expectation still is that the target will
be met.'
The future exchange rate of sterling, however, will be crucial to the
authorities' ability to meet the target. The report says that the 5 per cent
rise in sterling against its trade-weighted exchange rate index since
February 'has lowered somewhat' the risk of breaching the top of the target
range towards the end of this year and early next year. Any further increase
in the exchange rate would lower the probability of breaching the target, it
says. Conversely, a decrease in sterling's value would increase that risk.
The Bank expects Friday's retail prices figures for April to show a fall in
the underlying inflation rate from March's 3.5 per cent level, reflecting
the change from poll tax to the council tax. After that, however, the rate
will go back to 3.5 per cent by June as higher import prices pass through
into domestic retail prices.
It believes that underlying inflation will remain in the 3 per cent to 4 per
cent range in the next 18 months, largely because the inflation rate for
domestically produced goods will remain low. The output gap - between actual
output and a level of output in the UK economy consistent with a constant
rate of inflation - is likely to remain negative for some time, also
exerting downward pressure on inflation.
The Bank believes that inflation would probably have been constant 'over the
next year or so', had not the government announced plans to extend the scope
of value added tax to domestic fuel and power from April 1994. This increase
in indirect taxation means underlying inflation may rise next year.
The report says the main uncertainty surrounding inflation after 1994
concerns the response of domestic costs, such as wages and profits, to the
loss of purchasing power resulting from the depreciation of sterling since
last September.
If profit margins per unit of output or earnings per head do not rise,
increased demand will feed through into greater activity, and possibly
employment, without stimulating inflation, it says.
The Bank expresses some concern that the credibility of the government's
target of 1 per cent to 4 per cent underlying inflation over the life of
this parliament is still not reflected in prices on financial markets or in
opinion surveys.
It is vital that the target should be seen as a framework for policy over a
long period and that 'monetary and fiscal policy should be consistent with
achieving the target on a sustained basis', it says.
Bank of England Inflation Report, May 1993. Bulletin Group, Economics
Division, Bank of England, Threadneedle Street, London EC2R 8AH. Pounds 4.
Also included in the Bank Quarterly Bulletin, Vol 33, Number 2. Pounds 7.50
in the UK. Other subscription details from the Bulletin Group.
</TEXT>
