<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Major pledges to bolster industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night pledged to give substance to a new partnership
between government and industry by directing all of Whitehall's energy
towards broadening the economic recovery and strengthening the manufacturing
base.
In a speech to the Confederation of British Industry the prime minister
underlined his personal commitment to improving Britain's competitiveness.
That meant backing exporters, fostering public/private sector partnerships
to improve the nation's infrastructure, promoting free trade, removing
unnecessary government regulation and translating scientific research into
industrial innovation.
Mr Major had been told earlier by Mr Howard Davies, the director-general of
the CBI, that business wanted the government to listen to industry rather
than to its own rhetoric. The prime minister said in his speech that the
climate for industry to flourish was in place.
Admitting the mistakes that led to the inflationary boom of the late 1980s,
he added that the government had now delivered low inflation, low interest
rates and low tax rates.
Mr Major added: 'We have all learnt the hard lessons of those years. We will
not let inflation drive Britain off its course again.'
But he acknowledged that government also had a more direct role in helping
business at home and abroad. Decisions taken in Whitehall could help or
hinder industry in a 'thousand ways'.
Mr Major told the industrialists' annual dinner: 'All our policies - not
just our economic policy - need to be focused on the future strength of the
British economy.' He said that partnership between government and industry
would go well beyond the cash help for exporters and the tax cuts for
industry announced in the Autumn Statement and the Budget in March.
</TEXT>
