<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Recovery hopes rise sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXPECTATIONS of a strong economic recovery have risen sharply, Gallup's
latest survey of consumer confidence shows.
The survey recorded the most positive results for a year, with 43 per cent
of respondents expecting the economic situation to improve over the next 12
months. Only 22 per cent expected a deterioration. The balance of 21 per
cent expecting an improvement, the highest for 12 months, compares with
April's balance of 4 per cent expecting the situation to worsen. The
improvement in consumer sentiment appears to come from a big fall in the
numbers expecting unemployment to increase in the year ahead. Forty-nine per
cent thought unemployment would increase, compared with 68 per cent in
April.
