<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Prison policy not an open and shut case: Jail privatisation
is far from being a fait accompli
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S second privately run jail opens this month, and Prison Service
officials have started formulating recommendations to the government on the
extent and pace of a further, sustained programme of private-sector
involvement in prison management.
But Mr Derek Lewis, the former television executive who became
director-general of the Prison Service last month, is concerned about the
degree to which private-sector issues are dominating public discussion about
prisons. He says it is 'absolutely wrong' to see his appointment as a step
towards widespread privatisation.
When Blakenhurst, in Hereford and Worcester, opens this month it will be the
first privately managed prison to accommodate convicted prisoners. It
follows the opening of the Wolds remand prison, Humberside, last year. The
private sector is also bidding to manage Strangeways, Manchester, and will
be invited to bid for the new Doncaster prison under the government's market
testing programme.
All are either new or refurbished buildings. One of the tasks facing Mr
Lewis and his colleagues is to find ways of extending market testing to
established, operational prisons. The spate of escapes and other problems
when Group 4 took over Britain's first privately managed prisoner escort
contract last month demonstrated the difficulties of switching an existing
service from the public to the private sectors overnight.
Mr Lewis will recommend which types of prison are likely to be suitable for
private management, and suggest how to ensure that private-sector
involvement is sustained. 'The last thing anyone wants is something that is
going to be here today and gone tomorrow,' he said.
The appointment of a director-general from the private sector when the
government is opening the service to private management aroused concern
among prison staff and penal reform organisations. But Mr Lewis said he had
been given no brief to engineer widespread privatisation.
'It is inconceivable, for as far ahead as I can see, that public-sector
prisons will not remain the dominant element of the prison service. The
private sector has existed in the US for 10 years and represents no more
than a few per cent of the prison places.'
He believes Britain's limited experiment in private management has already
proved a powerful agent for change in the traditionally centralised prison
system, and hopes it will continue to act as a stimulus and test-bed for new
ideas. 'But it is quite wrong to see the private sector as anything other
than one element in a broad programme to improve the prison service as a
whole. 'By comparison with the private sector there is an enormous amount
more activity going on in the rest of the prison service,' he said.
'This includes a progressive programme of devolution to governors so that
they have responsibility and accountability for the performance of their
prisons. And we are developing a code of standards against which we can
measure the performance of each prison on a systematic basis. This is a
sea-change so far as the prison service is concerned.'
Mr Lewis has ambitious ideas for performance measurement, by establishing
comparisons between Britain's prisons and successful systems elsewhere in
the world.
He regards the Netherlands, Sweden, Denmark, Canada and parts of the US
system as good-quality services to share experience with Britain.
He has just completed a tour of US and Canadian prisons and believes that,
while Britain is in the lead in developing constructive relationships
between prisoners and officers, industrial programmes in North American
prisons are better developed.
He said: 'They are further down the road in increasing levels of wages for
prisoners and creating a virtuous circle of incentives. Progress in work is
an important factor in determining release dates in North America. That
seems to create a pretty powerful set of positive incentives, whereas our
incentives seem to be much more negative - if you misbehave you are punished
by loss of remission.'
Mr Lewis believes Britain might gain from adopting the greater staff
mobility found in the US and Canada, where probation officers sometimes
spend part of their careers as prison officers. He said: 'It gives better
understanding between functions, and eventually produces managers who are
much better equipped because they understand a number of activities at first
hand.'
</TEXT>
