<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Patten eases governors' quandary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PATTEN, the education secretary, yesterday gave school governors a
chance to avoid damaging confrontations with teachers and head teachers over
national curriculum tests.
Governors in England and Wales have a legal duty to implement the tests, in
spite of three teachers' unions boycotting them. Mr Patten has not heeded
calls by the National Association of Governors and Managers for the tests to
be made voluntary, but in a letter to governors yesterday he said they were
not expected to implement the tests if their teachers refused to administer
them.
He said governors will have performed their legal duties if they 'give a
clear lead that the professional course is to administer the tests', and
'satisfy themselves that teachers have been reminded of their duty to
administer the tests'.
Where boycotts do take place, governors are expected to 'consider carefully'
whether the tests can still be administered 'given the circumstances of the
school'. Finally, if any tests do take place, heads and governors are asked
to send the results to the department.
The Department for Education ruled out any attempt to impose sanctions on
governors, and said: 'We hope that as many people as possible will do the
tests. How governors, head teachers and local education authorities go about
doing it is a matter for them.'
Head teachers made it clear that the tests would not take place. Mr John
Sutton, general secretary of the Secondary Heads Association, said: 'The
simple fact is that our responsibility has been frustrated by the boycott of
the three unions.'
Secondary school head teachers in Hertfordshire yesterday told Mr Patten it
would be impossible to conduct tests for 14-year-olds this summer.
</TEXT>
