<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Cut-price advice plan for jobless
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANCHESTER Training and Enterprise Council yesterday launched a cut-price
redundancy counselling service for non-executive workers after trials
suggested it might reduce the time taken by some people to find new jobs.
The service, claimed to be the first of its kind offered by a Tec - the
employer-led bodies which administer government training schemes in England
and Wales - costs an employer Pounds 200 a day for up to 15 places on a
tutorial session with a qualified counsellor.
Daily rates in the private sector - usually for executives only - are said
to be in the Pounds 750 to Pounds 1,000 range.
Many smaller companies cannot afford to spend much on helping people they
make redundant - even though the government allows counselling costs to be
set against corporation tax.
Trials among six companies involved 200 redundant people. More than half
were back in work within three months.
