<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour electoral qualms reflected
in Plant report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THIS MORNING the Labour party's ruling National Executive Committee will
have before it the third report from the Plant Committee, a working party on
electoral systems chaired by Lord Plant, Professor of Politics at
Southampton University.
The report contains the committee's recommendations on appropriate electoral
systems for elections to the House of Commons, the House of Lords and the
European Parliament. If Labour adopts it the main opposition party will be
committed to electoral reform for the Commons for the first time since the
1920s.
The UK uses the first-past-the-post system for most elections, in which the
successful candidate is the one who receives the highest number of votes -
even if this is less than half the votes cast.
Opposition to this winner-takes-all approach has been growing among Labour
party members and that disquiet is reflected in the report, which says that
first-past-the-post fails to recognise the increasingly pluralistic nature
of British society.
The report says that the Commons would be strengthened if MPs represented
more closely the pattern of votes cast in various regions.
In seeking a new electoral system for the Commons, the report emphasises the
need to preserve the close link between MPs and constituencies to ensure
that elected representatives are accountable. This rules out electoral
systems such as Ireland's single transferable vote which has multi-member
constituencies, or list systems where voters choose parties rather than MPs
(as happens in Italy).
Lord Plant's personal preference was for a variant on Germany's electoral
system, with 500 MPs directly elected by constituencies and 150 others
nominated by parties so that seats in parliament reflect party support among
voters.
But he was unable to carry a majority for this system, largely because of
fears that it would create two classes of MPs. Instead, the committee went
for the supplementary vote, an electoral system devised by Mr Dale
Campbell-Savours, Labour MP for Workington, and used in no country in the
world.
Under the supplementary vote system, each voter would cast a first
preference and a second preference vote. If no candidate won more than half
the first preference votes, second preferences of the candidates with the
least votes would be redistributed to elect the candidate with the most
first and second preferences.
The supplementary vote system is not a proportional system - it could even
in some circumstances lead to a less proportional result than the current
first-past-the-post system.
But supplementary vote would involve the least change in the pattern of
representation in parliament. It would therefore probably encounter least
resistance if Labour ever tried to introduce it - many MPs would be
reluctant to vote for a change which might put them out of a job.
Its main advantage for its Labour supporters, however, is that it would have
reduced the number of Conservative MPs elected in the last election while
more than doubling the number of Liberal Democrats.
As Mr Campbell-Savours says in his contribution to the report: 'It is almost
inconceivable that there would not have been a Labour government, with the
support of the minority parties.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
HOW SUPPLEMENTARY VOTE MIGHT HAVE CHANGED THE 1992 GENERAL ELECTION
RESULT*
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                                       MPs under
                                  present first-        MPs under
                           % of    past-the-post    supplementary
Party                      vote           system      vote system
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Conservative                 42              336              288
Labour                       35              271              288
Liberal Democrat             18               20               47
N Ireland parties             2               17               17
Nationalists etc              3                7               11
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
*Assuming Conservatives win 40 per cent of Liberal Democrats' second
preference votes and Labour 60 per cent.
Figures calculated by Mr Dale Campbell-Savours MP
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
