<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Move to win over Tory rail rebels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS WILL try to reassure potential Tory rebels about the fate of
concessionary railcards after rail privatisation by emphasising that
attitudes to concessionary fares would be taken into account in awarding
franchises.
Only the disabled person's railcard is guaranteed by the privatisation
legislation. Ministers have argued that private-sector operators will want
to provide railcards voluntarily under the new arrangements - as British
Rail does now - because they are profitable.
But the issue is one of a handful on which uneasy Tory backbenchers are
seeking concessions from the government to make the proposals more workable
and more politically popular.
When the Commons debates the detail of the rail privatisation bill next week
Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, is expected to say that while
ministers do not believe the railcards should be rigidly protected in the
legislation, it would be reasonable for them to be a factor in the
competition for franchises.
The rebels are expecting to table their amendments to the legislation today,
and Sir Keith Speed, a former minister and a leading rebel, is likely to
meet Mr MacGregor before the end of the week.
Mr MacGregor saw more than 20 backbenchers on Monday evening and remains
confident that when the government's position on fares, line closures and
BR's ability to compete for the franchises is fully explained MPs are
broadly content with the plans.
While ministers are determined not to give way on allowing BR itself to
compete to run services they will seek to calm Tory fears about fare
increases and line closures.
They will emphasise that line-closure procedures will remain, and that fares
will still be regulated on monopoly services, arguing that on others
competition will prevent unreasonable rises.
</TEXT>
