<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Personal pensions under fire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PENSIONS NEED a radical overhaul, including the introduction of a new
national personal pension scheme and sharp increases in the basic state
payout, says the Institute for Public Policy Research.
The institute, a left-of-centre think tank, says in a review of UK state and
private pension provision published today that the new personal pension
scheme should invest in a new class of government bond.
It says that the government's increasing reliance on personal pensions for
retirement provision is badly misguided. The cost of operating a personal
pension is about four times that of state schemes and offers a reasonable
level of benefit to a very limited percentage of people, it says.
Personal pensions are not practical for those earning less than Pounds 8,000
to Pounds 9,000 a year because they cannot contribute enough to make the
contract worthwhile, it says. The average salary for those without an
occupational pension scheme, for whom personal pensions are advised, is
about Pounds 8,750.
The institute says the government should substantially increase state
pension benefit instead of relying on personal pensions. 'The higher basic
pension would be set, as a minimum, at the income support level for
pensioners. An allowance for housing costs would be paid in addition.'
It says the increases could be financed by restoration of the Treasury
supplement to the National Insurance Fund. The cost would be covered in part
by the abolition of the income tax age allowance.
Necessary tax increases among the working population could be phased in
sufficiently slowly to have minimal effects on take-home pay, it says.
The institute urges an overhaul of the state earnings-related pension
scheme, with the government creating a new national personal pension scheme
to be funded by member contributions - which would in effect be long-term
savings. It proposes the investment of these contributions in a new
government security - 'national insurance pension bonds' - with the capital
value linked to an index of national average earnings.
Interest would be in line with the assumptions underlying calculations of
tax incentives offered to those who contract out of this type of provision.
The institute is urging an overhaul of occupational pensions regulation
which would include rules protecting the benefits of those who switch jobs.
There should be industry schemes for those whose employer makes no pension
provision, it says.
Better Pensions for All, Bryn Davies. Institute for Public Policy Research,
30-32 Southampton Street, London WC2E 7RA. Pounds 7.50.
</TEXT>
