<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Overhaul of pensions proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK PENSIONS need a radical overhaul including sharp increases in the basic
state pension and the introduction of a new national personal pension scheme
which will invest in a new class of government bond, the Institute for
Public Policy Research urges.
In a review of UK state and private pension provision, the left-of-centre
think tank argues that the government's increasing reliance on personal
pensions for retirement provision is badly misguided.
The cost of operating a personal pension is about four times that of state
schemes and can offer a reasonable level of benefit to a very limited
percentage of the population, the institute says.
It adds that personal pensions are not practical for those earning less than
Pounds 8,000 to Pounds 9,000 a year because they cannot contribute enough to
make the contract worthwhile. The average salary for those without an
occupational pension scheme, for whom personal pensions are advised, is
about Pounds 8,750.
Instead of relying on private pensions, the government should substantially
increase state pension benefit, at a minimum, to the income support level
for pensioners and also pay a minimum housing benefit, the institute
proposes.
It says the increases could be financed by restoration of the Treasury
supplement to the National Insurance Fund and the cost be covered in part by
the abolition of the existing income tax age allowance.
Necessary tax increases among the working population could be phased in
sufficiently slowly to have minimal effects on workers' take-home pay.
The IPPR also urges an overhaul of the State Earnings Related Pension
Scheme, with the government creating a new National Personal Pension Scheme
to be funded by member contributions which will effectively be long-term
savings. It suggests the investment of these contributions in a new
government security - 'national insurance pension bonds' - with the capital
value linked to an index of national average earnings.
Interest would be in line with the assumptions underlying calculations of
tax incentives offered to those who contract out of this type of provision.
The IPPR is further urging an overhaul of occupational pensions regulation
which would include rules protecting the benefits of those who switch jobs,
among other things. And for those whose employer makes no pension provision,
there should be industry schemes.
Better Pensions for All, Bryn Davies. Institute of Public Policy Studies,
30-32 Southampton Street, London WC2E 7RA, Pounds 7.50
</TEXT>
