<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / The Danish Referendum: Vote cheers Nordic business and
political leaders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES and KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM, OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE DANISH referendum result was welcomed by Nordic politicians and business
leaders, who believe it will speed up their countries EC membership talks
and have a positive influence on sceptical public opinion. Sweden, Norway
and Finland are all due to hold referendums on EC membership in the next two
years.
'With a Danish No it would have been very difficult to get a Yes in Sweden,'
said Mr Bengt Westerberg, Sweden's deputy prime minister.
The result was also welcomed by Norwegian prime minister Mrs Gro Harlem
Brundtland although she warned that 'the issues we face are very different
from those faced by the Danes. We are preoccupied with energy, fish and
regional policy.'
However, with popular opinion in both Sweden and Norway against membership,
politicians in both countries face a difficult task in taking their
countries into the community. Some believe they may be forced to seek Danish
style opt-outs to take their electorates with them.
An opinion poll published in Norway yesterday showed 51 per cent of the
electorate against membership, four percentage points more than in April,
with only 30 per cent in favour.
A recent Swedish opinion poll showed 44 per cent of voters against the EC,
with 34 per cent in favour. The anti-vote in the country has ranged between
41 and 53 per cent since Denmark's first vote on Maastricht last June.
Relief over the outcome of the vote was underlined by Mrs Kaci Kullman Five,
leader of Norway's pro-EC opposition Conservative party. She said: 'If the
Danes had voted No, opposition in Norway would have been irreversible.'
Business leaders reacted positively to the news. Mr Magnus Lemmel, director
general of the Swedish Federation of Industries said: 'EC membership is very
important for us. We need to have exactly the same terms as our competitors.
We cannot afford to be discriminated against.'
But those opposing membership were not disheartened by the vote. Ms Eva
Britt Svensson, chairwoman of Sweden's 'No to the EC' group, predicted that
the Danish vote would further swing Swedish public opinion against the
community. 'People will realise that its political, monetary and economic
union they are voting for and not the EC,' she stated.
Sweden and Finland began negotiations on EC membership in February, and are
hoping to join the community in 1995. Norway, which rejected membership in
1972, began fresh negotiations on membership last month.
Mr Ingvar Carlsson, the leader of Sweden's opposition Social Democrat party,
said the Danes had taken a 'wise decision' which would open the way 'for a
common European fight against unemployment and social and union rights'.
</TEXT>
