<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Proposals for electoral change threaten to split Labour
party
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR MPs opposed to electoral reform launched a campaign yesterday against
a working party's proposals for sweeping changes to the way parliament is
elected.
The proposals, which are to be discussed today by Labour's ruling national
executive committee, are made in a report by the opposition's working party
on electoral systems, chaired by Lord Plant of Highfield.
The report recommends abolishing the first-past-the-post system used for
elections to the House of Commons in favour of an untried system known as
the supplementary vote. It also recommends switching to proportional
representation for elections to the European parliament and for the second
chamber Labour proposes to introduce to replace the House of Lords.
The NEC discussion was intended to launch a consultation period on the Plant
report before a decision at the autumn party conference. Now it looks likely
to open up a new split in the party, already deeply divided over internal
reforms such as the loosening of links with the trade unions.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, will be hoping to avoid an open split by
backing the idea of a national referendum on electoral reform at today's
meeting.
Mr Smith is cautious about electoral reform, although he is said to have
accepted the case for change. But a group of MPs opposed to reform launched
a campaign to retain the first-past-the-post system.
Mr Derek Fatchett, chairman of the group, warned that for a newly elected
Labour government to spend its first year or two on electoral reform would
be 'Labour's equivalent of a new Maastricht bill', in terms of its
divisiveness and irrelevance.
The Plant report says the present system fails to reflect the changing
nature of British society. It examines three options for changing the UK's
electoral system so that the number of MPs from each party more closely
reflects party support, without losing the direct link between MPs and
constituencies.
All three options would have left the Conservatives short of an overall
majority at the last election and would almost certainly have resulted in a
minority Labour government.
By a narrow majority, the Plant committee recommends that Labour should
adopt the supplementary-vote system devised by Mr Dale Campbell-Savours, MP
for Workington.
That would allow voters to express a second preference, which would be taken
into account if no candidate won more than 50 per cent of the
first-preference votes.
Other recommendations in the report include:
Introducing four-year fixed-term parliaments;
State funding for political parties;
Limits on national spending by parties in general elections.
Reforms split the party, Page 11
Editorial Comment, Page 25
</TEXT>
