<DATE>930519
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / Danish Yes vote boosts treaty: Maastricht wins 56.8% support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY and HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DENMARK delivered a decisive vote in favour of the Maastricht treaty on
European union last night, to the profound relief of its partners in the
European Community.
The Yes victory, by a margin of 56.8 per cent to 43.2 per cent with all the
votes counted, reversed last June's rejection of the treaty by Danish
voters. Last year's result had thrown into serious doubt the EC strategy for
closer economic and political union.
Yesterday, in a turnout of 86.2 per cent, Danes voted to accept Maastricht,
this time with the crucial proviso of the Edinburgh agreements which gave
Denmark a series of opt-outs from the treaty's key programmes.
Mr Poul Nyrup Rasmussen, the prime minister, claimed victory shortly after
the first computer predictions were broadcast. 'I am happy that it is such a
clear result . . . it is a very important Yes,' he said.
Mr Niels Helveg Petersen, foreign minister, proclaimed: 'This is good for
Denmark and it is good for Europe.' Looking forward to the EC summit in
Copenhagen next month, which Denmark will chair as current president of the
Community, Mr Helveg Petersen said: 'Denmark can speak with greater
authority.'
Ms Drude Dahlerup, spokeswoman of the anti-treaty June Movement, had
conceded defeat shortly after the first exit polls, saying: 'It's clearly a
disappointment. It's a historic decision going the wrong way.'
But she said the size of the No vote showed that: 'The people are still
divided and parliamentarians must listen to all those people who voted
against the treaty.'
Mr Jacques Delors, European Commission president, said last night that
Denmark's decision would provide 'a stimulus to the Community'. The Yes vote
would help the EC to leave behind a difficult period of 'inaction' at a time
when it faced 'many internal problems - especially economic stagnation and
rising unemployment'. Mr Delors added: 'For all these reasons, Europe needs
a new impulse.'
The EC welcomed the Danish vote, saying it would allow Denmark to continue
contributing to the process of European union. Mr Klaus Kinkel, German
foreign minister, said the vote was 'a rejection of the Euro-sceptics'. He
went on: 'By voting Yes, the Danish people have decided their future lies in
common with their partners in the EC on the basis of the Treaty on European
Union . . . I am happy that the Danish voters have acted with real European
responsibility.'
After Denmark, only Britain and Germany, where the treaty is being
challenged in the constitutional court, have not yet ratified Maastricht. Mr
Kinkel said he hoped all member states would now clear the way for
Maastricht ratification before parliaments went into recess for the summer.
Mr Karl Lamers, foreign affairs spokesman for the Christian Democrats in the
German parliament, said the vote meant 'the British cannot hide behind the
Danes. Such an attitude was always unworthy of them. Now they must decide
for themselves whether their answer is Yes or No.'
Sir Leon Brittan, EC commissioner for external economic affairs, said: 'The
Danes have decided after long and detailed analysis that, far from forcing
them down the road of an over- centralised and bureaucratic union, the
Maastricht treaty will strengthen the ties between European nations without
threatening their identity.'
Mr Hans van den Broek, commissioner for external political affairs,
described the outcome as 'an important day for Europe'.
'We are looking with high expectations towards London for the British House
of Commons to complete its ratification of the treaty,' he added. France,
which last June had initially urged EC partners to brush aside Denmark's
rejection of Maastricht, last night welcomed yesterday's vote.
The foreign ministry, with an eye to British ratification, said it was
important to implement Maastricht as soon as possible. In the first Danish
vote last June, the verdict went against ratification by 50.7 per cent to
49.3 per cent, a majority of only 46,000 votes out of almost 3.3m cast.
The Edinburgh EC summit last December granted Denmark opt-outs from the
treaty's provisions on a unified currency, defence policy, community-wide
legal and police co-operation, as well as union citizenship.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DKZ  Denmark, EC.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
