<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 93 / D-Mark hit by easing of tensions in ERM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE prospect of a Yes vote in the Danish referendum weakened the D-Mark
yesterday, as international investors took the view that such a result would
significantly ease tensions in Europe's exchange rate mechanism.
Several European currencies, including sterling and the Italian lira,
enjoyed strong rises against the D-Mark, as Danish opinion polls pointed to
a clear ratification of the Maastricht treaty and a period of calm in
Europe's fixed exchange rate system.
This reversed a trend of recent weeks in which investors, fearful of another
Danish No, sought a safe haven against currency turmoil and a renewed threat
to European economic and monetary union by buying D-Marks and Swiss francs.
German government bond prices also fell to the benefit of Italian and French
bonds.
Danish opinion polls helped the pound to close a pfennig higher against the
D-Mark on the day, at DM2.4875. The Italian lira was also a strong
performer, closing at L909.2 against the D-Mark from a previous close of
L914.9.
The dollar gained significantly from the D-Mark's weakness, rising more than
a pfennig to peak at DM1.6272 in Europe, and reaching a 7-week high. It
later closed in London at DM1.6240.
An additional factor pushing the dollar higher against the German currency
was speculation that the Federal Reserve's federal open market committee
would lean towards tightening monetary policy at its meeting in New York
yesterday.
Expectations of a rise in short-term US interest rates have followed last
week's US inflation figures, which were higher than anticipated. The results
of the meeting, which took place yesterday and continues today, will not be
known for some weeks.
Currencies, Page 43
