FT  18 MAY 93 / UK Company News: Plateau repeats its support for Dixon Motor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HOSTILE bid for Plateau Mining by Kingstream, a small Australian
exploration company, closes on Thursday and both sides have sent
communications to Plateau shareholders.
Kingstream says the rival proposal for Dixon Motor Holdings to reverse into
Plateau would result in Plateau shareholders having '10 per cent of a motor
dealership in the north of England which in 1992 had a turnover of Pounds
46m producing a net profit of only Pounds 250,000'.
Its own offer however would give shareholders 22 per cent of a steel-making
venture 'ideally placed to serve the booming south-east Asian market and
with a projected turnover in excess of Pounds 400m'.
Plateau's board continues to recommend the Dixon deal and suggests that 'the
few selective statements that Kingstream make about the Dixon Group give a
misleading impression.
'Dixon has a proven UK-based business, is consistently profitable and has
always been in a position to pay divi-dends.
'On the basis of its published accounts, Kingstream has had no profits, has
no net cash and has not paid dividends.'
Plateau says the Dixon proposals coupled with a disposal to Delta Gold, the
Australian mining group, are worth in the region of 7.6p a share, compared
with Kingstream's all-paper offer worth, at best, 4.8p.
