<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / International Company News: Xerox stock suffers after
chairman's warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEREMY BENNALLACK-HART
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
XEROX shares fell sharply yesterday after Mr Paul Allaire, chairman, warned
that second-quarter earnings in the company's core document processing
operations could drop below the Dollars 1.12-a-share level posted a year
ago.
However, he said he still expected full-year earnings for those operations
to show an increase on 1992.
Wall Street was surprised by the announcement and by the close Xerox shares
were down Dollars 3 1/8 at Dollars 72 1/4 in active trading. The opening was
delayed by a backlog of sell orders.
Mr Allaire said the earnings fall reflected fundamental changes in the
management of the company's document processing business, the realignment of
the US salesforce and continued weak economic conditions.
These factors had already affected first-quarter results, released last
month, which showed overall net income of Dollars 189m, or Dollars 1.77 a
share, against a loss of Dollars 529m, or Dollars 5.68, in the same period
last year when the company took accounting charges. Income from the document
processing business was Dollars 125m, or Dollars 1.12, against Dollars 103,
or 91 cents. Revenues were unchanged at Dollars 3.3bn.
Mr Allaire said yesterday that, after the second quarter, 'we expect sales
momentum to increase as we realise the benefits of the sales
reorganisation'.
His comments, in a conference with security analysts, were made in view of
the planned offering of 6m shares, announced in March, which the company
said would go ahead this summer.
Mr Walter Fitzgerald, an equity analyst with RAS Securities, said the stock
market was probably overreacting yesterday. The company's new products were
going well and, although European markets remained flat, it was on target,
he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Xerox Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3861 Photographic Equipment and Supplies.
</IN>
