<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / US West finds cable role in TWE deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE announcement that US West, one of the seven US regional 'Baby Bells',
will invest Dollars 2.5bn (Pounds 1.62bn) in Time Warner Entertainment, part
of Time Warner, the giant media and entertainment conglomerate, marks an
important new step in the fast-evolving relationship between the US
telecommunications and cable industries, writes Nikki Tait in New York.
To date, that relationship has largely been confrontational - a battle over
who will bring communications into US homes over the next decade, with
complex regulatory restrictions muddying a simple competitive fight. Now, it
seems, co-operation may be the order of the day. 'This knocks the regulatory
paradigm into a cocked hat,' remarked Richard McCormick, US West's chairman.
At a financial level, the deal is complex. Essentially, US West will put up
Dollars 1.5bn when the deal closes, hopefully later this year. The remaining
money will be supplied over four years. This will give US West a 25.51 per
cent interest in Time Warner Entertainment, which covers the parent's filmed
entertainment, programming and cable interests. Time Warner will continue to
own 63.27 per cent of TWE, and have operating control of much of the
division. Remaining equity will be spilt between Itochu (previously C. Itoh)
and Toshiba, existing partners in TWE.
But the relationship between Time Warner and US West is expected to run
deeper. Out of US West's total investment, Dollars 1bn will be devoted to
developing Time Warner's planned 'full-service network'. This is the
ambitious interactive cable-based home entertainment and communications
network, which the company detailed in January.
According to Time Warner yesterday, capital expenditure on cable is
currently about Dollars 400m a year. Between 1994 and 1998, it is expected
to average about Dollars 800m annually - and most of this will go on
developing the full-services network. US West's Dollars 1bn will be welcome.
The other Dollars 4bn, according to Time Warner, will come from internally
generated cash-flows.
The full-service network venture will be run jointly and involve both
groups' employees. 'US West brings intimate knowledge of network switching
(which) permits efficient tracking and billing of the myriad transactions
that will cross the network,' said Mr Gerald Levin, Time Warner's chairman.
Other Time Warner executives noted US West's experience in selling to the
business community. And US West can boast direct experience of working
alongside a cable company: it has already linked up with TCI, the nation's
largest cable operator, to provide telephone and cable services in the UK.
Lex, Page 18; TCI results, Page 24
