<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Television really can damage health. I feel unwell after sampling the
surrealistically bad chat show This Morning (ITV, 10.35am weekdays).
Presented by an apparently live married couple, This Morning is television's
equivalent of anthrax; insidious and incurable.
Things improve later. One of today's oddest items is the last of the
erratically absorbing series Without Walls (Channel 4, 9pm). Tonight's
programme features amateur film-footage of a weekend in 1939, rare colour
film of Adolf Hitler and his repellant cronies enjoying a Munich arts
festival.
40 Minutes (BBC2, 9.50pm) is regularly strong. Tonight it deals with the
horrendous subject of rape in a high-risk manner, by bringing face-to-face a
victim and a convicted rapist. Probably compulsive viewing, but one wonders
why.
The evening's laurels go to the classic SF movie The Day The Earth Stood
Still (Channel 4, 10pm). The alien Michael Rennie visits Washington DC with
a message of peace. He discovers humanity is rather unpleasant. A cynical
view induced, no doubt, by watching This Morning.
</TEXT>
