<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Business and the Law: Lords to probe Community competition
rules - Briefs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE House of Lords Select Committee on the European Communities has launched
an inquiry into the enforcement of EC competition rules. A sub-committee
chaired by Lord Slynn, Britain's former judge at the European Court of
Justice, will concentrate its inquiries on the procedures of the European
Commission and levels of decision-making.
Following concern expressed by the Court of First Instance in Luxembourg,
the committee will examine:
whether Commission procedures are flawed;
whether staff shortages and budgetary constraints within the competition
directorate are delaying decision-making;
and it will look into the Commission's publicly-expressed wish that more
enforcement of competition rules should take place at national level.
The committee's previous examination of competition practice - in 1982  -
resulted in improvements in procedures. The sub-committee will also examine
procedural operations and possible revision of the thresholds of the Merger
Regulation.
</TEXT>
