<PROFILE>_AN-DERDAACQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930518
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Unknown quantity on the party line
 -The rise of an MP with a business background
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR Tory MPs urging the promotion of 'exciting new faces' in the next
reshuffle in order to regain the political initiative, Mr Roger Freeman is
an unlikely prospect for the cabinet.
Among the growing number who would settle for competence, however, there is
less surprise that his name has been appearing third or fourth on the
shortlists of those tipped for the cabinet. The Commons debate on rail
privatisation next week will determine whether it stays there.
So far, Mr Freeman and the bill he has piloted through the detailed 100-plus
hours of committee discussion have survived the process almost unscathed.
In January last year, however, he underwent some days of public apologies
for remarks that post-privatisation franchise holders might want to run
'cheap and cheerful' services for typists and different services at other
times. That apart, he has attracted favourable reviews from backbenchers for
his courtesy and diligence.
Some rightwingers suggest Mr Freeman as the next Treasury chief secretary
because of his numeracy and mastery of detail - he qualified as an
accountant. But to many of his colleagues, he remains an unknown quantity.
Since becoming an MP in 1983, he has had little opportunity to express
personal views rather than departmental policy. Seven of his 10 years as the
first Tory MP for Kettering since John Profumo have been spent as a
minister: first at the Ministry of Defence, then at the Department of Health
and, since 1990, at transport.
He says the reason he went into politics was that he is 'fascinated' with
the process of government and of parliament. 'I don't think I'd make a very
good backbencher - I like the challenge of translating a policy into
results.'
While a backbench MP, he was on the influential cross-party Treasury
committee, and in October 1985 was one of the Tories who voted -
unsuccessfully - for the committee to recommend a decision in principle to
enter the European exchange rate mechanism, instead of concluding that there
should be no change in the status quo over the short to medium term.
Having spent almost 20 years before entering parliament as a partner at
Lehman Brothers, the US investment bank, in charge of the international
office, he opposes political union and says he is 'a European for business
reasons'.
Overall, Mr Freeman gives the impression that he is a Conservative largely
for business, rather than political, reasons.
He strongly believes in enterprise, innovation and effort; in bringing the
private sector into government affairs; and in a low rate of direct
taxation, together with moves towards ending tax perks and allowances.
He takes an austere view of the politician's role - though supporting the
education reforms and having worked on the health service reforms, for
example, he has not campaigned in his constituency for individual schools to
become grant-maintained or for GPs to become fund-holding practices.
</TEXT>
