<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Unions warned in Labour links row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNION leaders were warned yesterday that they risked damaging the Labour
party's reputation by opposing reforms of their links with the party urged
by Mr John Smith, its leader, Ralph Atkins writes.
As leaders of six of Britain's biggest unions prepared to meet later this
week to discuss alternatives to Mr Smith's proposals, Mr Roy Hattersley,
former deputy leader, warned that Labour would be 'cruelly handicapped' if
it continued to be regarded as being dominated by trade unions.
Labour party officials say Mr Smith is braced for a showdown with unions
over his plans to introduce one-member-one-vote for the selection and
re-selection of Labour parliamentary candidates.
Opposing him are likely to be the Transport and General Workers' union, the
GMB general union, the MSF technicians' union, the UCW communications union
and the RMT, the rail and seamen's union.
