<DATE>930518
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Minister tells Tories to reject
free-market dogma
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the rising stars of Mr John Major's government last night called on
the Conservative party to abandon the 'slavish adherence' to the economic
dogma which characterised the politics of the 1980s.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, the financial secretary to the Treasury, said the
collapse of Eastern bloc socialism gave the Conservatives the opportunity to
shed their polarised image as a party content simply 'to leave things to the
market'.
His comments came as Mr Major prepared to underline to the Confederation of
British Industry his commitment to industrial revival by calling for a
partnership between government and industry across all Whitehall policy
areas.
He will reaffirm his determination to encourage the joint financing of
infrastructure projects by the public and private sectors.
The prime minister will also tell the CBI annual dinner tonight that the
white paper on science policy being drawn up by Mr William Waldegrave,
public service minister, will be geared towards improving British industrial
competitiveness.
In his lecture to the Tory Reform Group last night, Mr Dorrell underlined
the break with Thatcherite 'ideology' by arguing that dogmatic attachment to
market economics had represented a 'profound misrepresentation of the true
Tory position'.
Mr Dorrell, who is tipped for membership of the cabinet in the next
reshuffle, said that the party should instead recognise that market
economics was no more than a means of delivering political objectives.
Central to those objectives were higher living standards, but they included
also such concepts of social stability, evolutionary change, individual
responsibility and the rule of law. 'Economic policies must, therefore, be
shaped by our commitment to those wider political objectives, not simply the
arid dictates of academic economics.'
Mr Dorrell stressed that this did not imply any weakening of the
government's resolve to deliver price stability. The relative experiences of
Britain and Germany in the post-war period underlined the damage - economic,
social and industrial - wrought by failure to control inflation.
Admitting candidly the government's past mistakes he added: 'There is no
secret why the recession in Britain was longer than elsewhere - we had a
higher rate of inflation than our competitors in the 1980s. Recession
follows inflation as night follows day.'
Mr Dorrell also emphasised that the disciplines of the marketplace provided
the essential basis for wealth creation by matching the output of producers
with the changing needs of consumers.
But adopting a rhetoric calculated to dismay those on the right of the Tory
party who cling to the free market doctrines expounded by Baroness Thatcher,
he added: 'Market disciplines are not the Holy Grail.'
Governments would also want to define the parameters in which market
conclusions were acceptable, he said.
</TEXT>
