<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: EC move to protect consumers
opposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is to continue to resist attempts by the European Commission
to include financial services in a new EC directive on distance selling,
Baroness Denton, consumer affairs minister, told the House of Lords last
night.
She maintained that financial services would not fit well in the framework
of the regulation. It was designed to provide greater protection for
consumers as the single European market and developments in
telecommunications led to more products being sold across national borders.
Lord Peston, from the Labour front bench, and Lord Thomson of Monifieth, for
the Liberal Democrats, both argued for the inclusion of financial services
in the scope of the new directive, but Lady Denton stressed that the sector
was already subject to detailed regulation at both national and EC level.
She accepted that there might well be a case for providing further
protection for consumers, but insisted that this could best be achieved by
building on measures already in force or being developed.
Lady Denton also warned against plans to give consumers an automatic refund
on any disputed credit card sale where proper electronic identification of
the card itself had not been made.
The EC draft directive would mean that a telephone sale by credit card
should be void if challenged by the cardholder.
Baroness Denton said: 'The government understands the need for safeguards
against abuse of credit cards, but everyone is concerned that the current
provisions in the proposal are too heavily loaded in favour of the
consumer.'
The draft directive also addresses the question of unsolicited advertising
by fax, stressing the need for privacy, but with no firm proposals.
